These results corroborate theoretical expectations: deviations from P0 distort the Page curve and risk remnants (large $c$), weaker scrambling can be tolerable for the entropy metric at small scales, and larger $\varepsilon$ increases local deviations (bounded by P3).

\section{Predictions and Falsifiability}
\label{sec:predictions}

HMC predicts specific, falsifiable signatures: $g^{(2)}$ comb sidebands in analogue Hawking radiation~\cite{Barcelo:2011} and soft memory echoes plus QNM phase correlations in ringdown signals~\cite{Cardoso:2016}. Quantitative dependencies on $\varepsilon\sim 1/S_{\rm BH}$ and $\tau_{\rm mem}\sim \beta\log S_{\rm BH}$ follow from Eqs.~\eqref{eq:kernel_schwarzian} and \eqref{eq:kernel_4d}. Table~\ref{tab:quantitative_predictions} summarizes orders of magnitude across frameworks.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Quantitative predictions summary (orders of magnitude).}
\label{tab:quantitative_predictions}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\toprule
Framework & $g^{(2)}$ amplitude & Memory time & Ringdown phase corr. \\
\midrule
HMC (this work) & $O(1/S_{\rm BH})$ & $\sim \beta\log S_{\rm BH}$ & $O(1/S_{\rm BH})$ \\
Hawking (Markovian) & $0$ & --- & $0$ \\
Soft hair (static) & $\lesssim O(1/S_{\rm BH})$ (non-dynamic) & $\sim \beta$ & small/static \\
Islands (entropy only) & not local in $g^{(2)}$ & --- & model-dependent \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\section{Discussion and Outlook}
\label{sec:discussion}

\paragraph{Limitations and future work.}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
\item \emph{Generalization to 4D:} We provided a membrane-paradigm derivation for $\Xi^R_{4\mathrm{D}}$ (Eq.~\ref{eq:kernel_4d}), but a fully microscopic, non-perturbative derivation in asymptotically flat 4D gravity remains a priority. Iyer–Wald~\cite{Iyer:1994} and Brown–York~\cite{BrownYork:1993} tools, plus first-principles quantization of horizon edge modes, should yield sharpened correlators and higher-order corrections.
\item \emph{Nature of scramblers:} We complemented toy models with an exact small-scale comb and ablations. A systematic study of approximate $t$-design depth versus entropy recovery in larger Hilbert spaces is left to future work.
\item \emph{Backreaction:} We quantified cumulative corrections as $O(1/S_{\rm BH})$. A more refined Einstein–Langevin treatment, including stochastic fluctuations from the kernel, would further solidify the gentle-backreaction claim.
\item \emph{Numerics:} Full dynamical simulations at larger scales remain an open computational challenge; tensor-network approximations for memory kernels and local circuits may be promising.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Robustness.}
Our ablations and exact comb checks empirically validate P0–P4’s necessity and robustness: departures from the area-memory law or excessive non-gentleness degrade the Page curve and local smoothness, while moderate deviations from perfect scrambling preserve unitarity at small scales.

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

We proposed the Horizon Memory Comb as a unifying, dynamical resolution to the black hole information problems. We derived the HMC postulates and the memory kernel’s explicit structure from edge-mode boundary theories, nearly-AdS$_2$/JT gravity, and a new membrane-paradigm derivation for 4D asymptotically flat black holes. The derived kernels have amplitude $\sim 1/S_{\rm BH}$, inherit thermal structure, and encode the temporal nonlocality that unitarizes evaporation while preserving local smoothness. Our methods, ablations with statistical tests, and an exact small-scale comb simulation strengthen the framework’s rigor and falsifiability, opening a path to empirical probes via analogue systems and gravitational-wave astronomy.

