\section{Appendix D: Schwarzian Correlators and the Memory Kernel}
\label{app:schwarzian_appendix}

We outline the derivation of Eq.~\eqref{eq:kernel_schwarzian}. The Schwarzian action $S_{\rm Schw}[f]=\frac{C}{2}\int du\, \{f(u),u\}$ yields a reparametrization mode whose fluctuations at finite temperature are controlled by $C\propto S_{\rm BH}$; see~\cite{Maldacena:2016SYK, MSY:2016, Jensen:2016}. The operator $\mathcal{O}_{\rm Schw}(u)$ that couples to matter deforms boundary time and can be linearized in the small-fluctuation regime, $\mathcal{O}_{\rm Schw}\sim \partial_u^3 \epsilon(u)+\cdots$, with $\epsilon$ the Goldstone reparametrization fluctuation. The Kubo formula for the retarded kernel reads
\begin{equation}
\Xi^R(u) = i g^2 \Theta(u)\, \langle[\mathcal{O}_{\rm Schw}(u),\mathcal{O}_{\rm Schw}(0)]\rangle_\beta.
\end{equation}
Using known finite-temperature correlators of Schwarzian operators~\cite{Maldacena:2016SYK}, one obtains the digamma form in frequency space (Eq.~\ref{eq:kernel_schwarzian}). At low frequencies ($|\omega|\beta\ll 1$) this behaves as $\Xi^R(\omega)\sim \frac{g^2}{C}\,\big(\psi'(1)\,(\beta\omega)^2+\cdots\big)$, while at high frequencies ($|\omega|\beta\gg 1$) logarithmic tails appear. In time domain, this produces oscillatory-decaying kernels consistent with the comb sidebands observed in Sec.~\ref{sec:experiments}.

\section{Appendix E: Code availability and reproducibility}
\label{app:code}
We provide a self-contained script that generates the datasets used by the figures and tables in the main text. It exposes functions to:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
\item generate Page-curve toy-model data with reproducible seeds,
\item generate $g^{(2)}$ correlation curves with 95\% CIs,
\item perform ablation studies with statistical testing (Welch tests) and FDR correction,
\item run a minimal exact comb simulation with explicit unitaries and partial traces.
\end{itemize}
Default parameters (seeds, run counts, and horizon memory dimensions) are documented in the script header. All plots in the paper use embedded data files generated by these routines to ensure reproducibility without external dependencies.

